(2) serpae-scipio was the son of Aemilius Paulus Macedonicus, who defeated Perseus at Pydna, 168 rac, and thus completed the conquest of Macedonia. He was born 185 rac, and was adopted by the eldest son of Scipio Africanus. By virtue of this adoption, his full name became Publius Cornelius Scipio Aemilianus, to which was afterwards added Africanus, iu honor of his victory over Carthage. His first expe- rience as a soldier was gained under his father at Pydna. In the year 151 rac. he scrved as military tribune in Spain, aud won distinction by his cnergy and persoual courage. In the Third Punic War, the Romans, disheartened by the ill success of their generals, elected Scipio consul for the year 147 rac, though he had not yet reached the legal age, and gave him the chief command, in the hope that he would quiclrly terminate the conflict, and add new lustcr to Roman arms. Their confidence was not misplaced. In the following spring he captured the city, utterly overthrcw the Carthaginien power, and received as his own reward a magnificent triumph at Rome. Again, in 133 rac, he was called upon to retrieve losses due to the mismanagement aud incorupetency of others, and brought to a successful issue the Numantina War, which had been prolonged‚ to the iujury and discredit of Rome, ten years.
